As Basil Bourque said, Normalizer has *nothing* to do with Java Unicode escapes.  Do not attempt to use it for this;  it cannot do what you want at all.

First, let’s clarify something.  Writing this:

    String s = &quot;\u00e0&quot;;

is **exactly the same** as writing this:

    String s = &quot;&#224;&quot;;

The compiler (not the Java runtime) will interpret any `\u` escape sequence as if it were the actual codepoint.  Regardless of which method is used for writing the string value, there is no `\` or `u` in the string.  At all.

However, if for some reason you have input that mistakenly added a literal backslash character, followed by a `u`, followed by four hex digits:

    // This is NOT a Unicode escape.  It is a six-character string.
    String s = &quot;\\u00e0&quot;;

You can replace each such sequence using a regular expression [Matcher](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/19/docs/api/java.base/java/util/regex/Matcher.html):

    Matcher hexMatcher = Pattern.compile(&quot;\\\\u(\\p{XDigit}{4})&quot;).matcher(s);
    String fixed = hexMatcher.replaceAll(
        r -&gt; String.format(&quot;%c&quot;, Integer.valueOf(r.group(1), 16)));

