Those are objects which are already been placed in the scope by the servlet container, so that it&#39;s accessible by EL (Expression Language), such as the [`PageContext`][1], [`HttpServletRequest#getParameter()`][2], [`HttpServletRequest#getHeader()`][3] and so on. Those are just for convenience so that you don&#39;t need to use old-fahioned *scriptlets* to grab them. 

So instead of for example

    &lt;%= pageContext.getSession().getMaxInactiveInterval() %&gt;&lt;br&gt;
    &lt;%= request.getParameter(&quot;foo&quot;) %&gt;&lt;br&gt;
    &lt;%= request.getHeader(&quot;user-agent&quot;) %&gt;&lt;br&gt;
    &lt;%  for (Cookie cookie : request.getCookies()) { // Watch out with NPE!
            if (cookie.getName().equals(&quot;foo&quot;)) {
                out.write(cookie.getValue());
            }
        }
    %&gt;&lt;br&gt;

you can just do

    ${pageContext.session.maxInactiveInterval}&lt;br&gt;
    ${param.foo}&lt;br&gt;
    ${header[&#39;user-agent&#39;]}&lt;br&gt;
    ${cookie.foo}&lt;br&gt;

You see that they follows the JavaBean conventions to be accessed (i.e. you can just invoke the getters the JavaBean way). You see that I used the brace notation `[]` to get the `user-agent`, that&#39;s because the `-` is a reserved character in EL, so `${header.user-agent}` isn&#39;t going to work, it would try to return the result of `request.getHeader(&quot;user&quot;) - pageContext.findAttribute(&quot;agent&quot;)` which is obviously not going to work.

For an overview of them all, check the chapter [**Implicit Objects**][4] in the Java EE tutorial.


  [1]: http://java.sun.com/javaee/5/docs/api/javax/servlet/jsp/PageContext.html
  [2]: http://java.sun.com/javaee/5/docs/api/javax/servlet/ServletRequest.html#getParameter%28java.lang.String%29
  [3]: http://java.sun.com/javaee/5/docs/api/javax/servlet/http/HttpServletRequest.html#getHeader%28java.lang.String%29
  [4]: http://java.sun.com/javaee/5/docs/tutorial/doc/bnahq.html#bnaij

